const e=JSON.parse('[{"id":"app-overview","title":"What This App Is About","subtitle":"A workspace for importing CSV data, shaping it, and writing Lisp against it.","summary":"This app combines sheet editing, hidden Lisp prelude generation, a code editor, runnable examples, and lightweight docs in one place.","tags":["overview","workspace","csv","lisp"],"content":["The app is designed around a simple workflow: bring in CSV data or create sheets from scratch, give columns types, and then use that data from Lisp without cluttering the visible editor.","Sheets are edited visually, but they also generate hidden bindings that the runtime and editor can use. That means you can work with data-backed code while keeping your main source focused on the logic you care about.","Functions let you keep reusable helpers in a separate workspace, test them in isolation, and include them into the hidden context only when you want them available.","The editor is paired with execution, console output, result inspection, and documentation so the app works as a single place to explore data, learn the language, and build small Lisp programs.","The Learn section is part of that workflow too: it gives you runnable examples, reference material, and miniature sheets so you can study concepts in the same environment where you actually write code."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Read imported sheet data","description":"Example code can call the generated column function from the mini sheet shown above.","code":"(people/name)"},{"title":"Use sheet data inside code","description":"The hidden sheet bindings can be pulled into normal Lisp expressions.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\nages"}]},{"id":"learn-page-overview","title":"How This Learn Page Works","subtitle":"Search topics, expand entries, run examples, and inspect mini sheets.","summary":"The Learn page is a lightweight documentation workspace with searchable entries, runnable editors, and optional example sheets.","tags":["learn","overview","examples"],"content":["Use the search box at the top to find a topic, concept, or function reference. Results are filtered across titles, subtitles, summaries, tags, and body text.","Each entry expands to show the written explanation, optional example sheets, and one or more runnable editor examples.","Mini sheets are defined in JSON as CSV text plus schema. They are shown as tables on the page and are also converted into hidden Lisp bindings for the example editors below them.","When you run an example, the editor compiles the example code together with the hidden prelude generated from the entry\'s mini sheets.","If a learn sheet exposes column types, changing them updates the generated hidden prelude for that entry\'s examples without affecting the main workspace.","The Learn page is lazy-loaded, so its content only downloads when you open the Learn tab."],"tables":[{"name":"demo","csv":"topic,level\\nSearch,1\\nRun,2\\nInspect,3","schema":[{"name":"topic","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"level","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Read from the demo sheet","description":"Example editors can use the hidden bindings generated from the mini sheet shown above.","code":"(demo/topic)"},{"title":"Run code with hidden prelude","description":"This example reads a generated column function from the demo sheet and returns it.","code":"(let levels (demo/level))\\nlevels"}]},{"id":"sheet-columns","title":"Sheet Columns Become Functions","subtitle":"Imported sheet columns are exposed as callable bindings.","summary":"Each imported sheet column is available as file_name/column_name and only evaluates when called, so repeated calls inside loops should be avoided.","tags":["sheets","columns","lambda"],"content":["CSV data is loaded into hidden context as one function per column. That keeps the editor clean while still making the data available to examples and user code.","You can call a generated column function directly to get the full column vector, or combine it with your own code to compute derived values.","These generated bindings are lazy, but they are not memoized. That means repeated calls can rebuild the same full column vector more than once.","The best pattern is to call a sheet column once, bind it locally, and then use that local value inside loops, reduces, or repeated lookups.","Avoid patterns like `(get (people/age) i)` inside a loop body. Prefer `(let ages (people/age))` once before the loop, then `(get ages i)` inside it."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Read a generated column","description":"Call the generated age column function from the imported people sheet.","code":"(people/age)"},{"title":"Bind the result locally","description":"Assign the generated column to a local name and inspect it.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\nages"},{"title":"Hoist before repeated access","description":"Call the sheet column once and reuse the local binding instead of calling it from inside repeated work.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(get names 0)"}]},{"id":"sum-columns","title":"Summing Columns","subtitle":"Use sum, reduce, and zip to turn numeric columns into totals.","summary":"Column functions return vectors, so the normal vector tools work directly for totals, subtotals, and derived sums.","tags":["columns","sum","reduce","zip","analysis"],"content":["A generated numeric column can be summed directly once you call it.","If you need a derived total, zip related columns together first and then map or reduce over the paired rows.","This is the standard pattern for revenue-style calculations: one column for quantity, one for price, one total expression."],"tables":[{"name":"orders","csv":"item,qty,price\\nBook,2,12\\nPen,5,3\\nLamp,1,40","schema":[{"name":"item","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"qty","type":"Int"},{"name":"price","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Sum one numeric column","description":"Call the generated quantity column and sum it directly.","code":"(sum (orders/qty))"},{"title":"Sum a derived line-total column","description":"Zip quantity and price together, multiply row-wise, then sum the result.","code":"(|> (zip { (orders/qty) (orders/price) })\\n    (map (lambda { qty price } (* qty price)))\\n    sum)"}]},{"id":"group-columns","title":"Grouping and Counting","subtitle":"Build tables keyed by a column to summarize repeated values.","summary":"For grouped analysis, reduce over row indices or a key column and accumulate into a Table.","tags":["grouping","tables","counting","analysis"],"content":["Grouping usually means turning one column into keys and storing all related rows or values under each key.","A Table is a good target for this because you can check whether a key already exists and then push or update in place.","This style works well for counting categories, collecting related values, or building quick indexes from imported sheets."],"tables":[{"name":"departments","csv":"department_id,department_name,manager_id\\n10,Administration,200\\n20,Marketing,201\\n30,Purchasing,114\\n40,Human Resources,203\\n50,Shipping,121\\n60,IT,103\\n70,Public Relations,204\\n80,Sales,145","schema":[{"name":"department_id","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"department_name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"manager_id","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Count departments per manager","description":"Reduce over the manager column and count how many departments each manager owns.","code":"(Table/entries\\n  (reduce (lambda a manager\\n            (do\\n              (if (Table/has? manager a)\\n                  (Table/set! a manager (+ 1 (Table/get-unsafe manager a)))\\n                  (Table/set! a manager 1))\\n              a))\\n          (Table/new)\\n          (departments/manager_id)))"},{"title":"Group department names by manager","description":"Use reduce/i so you can pull matching values from another column while grouping.","code":"(let department_names (departments/department_name))\\n(Table/entries\\n  (reduce/i (lambda (a manager i)\\n              (let dep (get department_names i))\\n                (if (Table/has? manager a)\\n                    (push! (Table/get-unsafe manager a) dep)\\n                    (Table/set! a manager [dep]))\\n                a)\\n            (Table/new)\\n            (departments/manager_id)))"}]},{"id":"cycle-detection","title":"Finding Cycles","subtitle":"Detect loops in reference data or directed edges.","summary":"Cycle detection is useful for linked references, graph edges, and suspicious repeated flows in imported data.","tags":["cycles","graphs","floyd","analysis"],"content":["A simple linked-reference sheet can be checked with Floyd\'s tortoise-and-hare algorithm.","When your data is already shaped as source and target columns, the graph helpers can search for arbitrary directed cycles.","The built-in cycle helpers are index-based, so they work naturally with generated columns and do not require turning everything into row objects first."],"tables":[{"name":"links","csv":"id,ref\\n1,2\\n2,3\\n3,4\\n4,2","schema":[{"name":"id","type":"Int"},{"name":"ref","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Detect a linked cycle with Floyd","description":"Treat ref as the next pointer and use floyd/cycle? to detect whether the chain loops.","code":"(let joined (zip { (links/id) (links/ref) }))\\n(floyd/cycle?\\n  (lambda pair (get joined (- (snd pair) 1)))\\n  (lambda (a b) (= (fst a) (fst b)))\\n  (get joined 0)\\n  (length joined))"},{"title":"Detect any directed cycle in edge columns","description":"The graph helper works directly on row indices plus from/to columns.","code":"(graph/has-cycle?\\n  (range 0 (- (length (links/id)) 1))\\n  (map Integer->String (links/id))\\n  (map Integer->String (links/ref)))"}]},{"id":"column-lookups","title":"Lookups and Row Alignment","subtitle":"Use enumerate, zip, and Table indexes to connect related columns.","summary":"A lot of data work comes down to keeping row positions aligned or building quick lookup tables from one column to another.","tags":["lookups","enumerate","zip","tables","joins"],"content":["Generated columns stay aligned by row index, so enumerate and zip are often enough for lightweight join-like tasks.","If you need repeated lookups, build a Table once from an id column and then query it while processing another column.","This is a useful pattern for app code where the data is already imported and typed."],"tables":[{"name":"users","csv":"user_id,name\\nU001,Alice\\nU002,Bob\\nU003,Carla","schema":[{"name":"user_id","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Attach row numbers to a column","description":"Enumerate gives you row index plus value, which is useful for later lookups or sorting.","code":"(enumerate (users/name))"},{"title":"Build an id -> name lookup table","description":"Reduce over aligned id/name columns and create a reusable Table for later lookups.","code":"(let names (users/name))\\n(|> (users/user_id)\\n    (reduce/i (lambda (a user_id i) (Table/set! a user_id (get names i)) a) (Table/new))\\n    (Table/entries))"}]},{"id":"date-helpers","title":"Date Helpers","subtitle":"Parse ISO timestamps into integer vectors and bucket them by day or hour.","summary":"A small Date helper layer is enough for common CSV analysis tasks like grouping by day, grouping by hour, and pulling out year or month parts.","tags":["date","timestamp","iso","grouping","analysis"],"content":["A practical shape is to parse ISO UTC timestamps like 2024-03-01T09:12:00Z into [year month day hour minute second].","Once timestamps are vectors of ints, you can pull parts out with Date/year, Date/month, Date/day, and Date/hour.","For grouping, small helpers like Date/ymd and Date/ymdh are enough for day buckets and hour buckets."],"tables":[{"name":"events","csv":"timestamp,amount\\n2024-03-01T09:12:00Z,10\\n2024-03-01T09:45:00Z,15\\n2024-03-01T10:05:00Z,20\\n2024-03-02T09:00:00Z,25","schema":[{"name":"timestamp","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"amount","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Parse one ISO timestamp","description":"Turn a timestamp string into [year month day hour minute second].","code":"(let Date/iso-z->Vector\\n  (lambda ts\\n    [\\n      (String->Integer (slice 0 4 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 5 7 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 8 10 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 11 13 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 14 16 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 17 19 ts))\\n ]))\\n\\n(Date/iso-z->Vector \\"2024-03-01T09:12:00Z\\")"},{"title":"Bucket timestamps by day","description":"Parse each timestamp and keep only the year, month, and day for grouping.","code":"(let Date/iso-z->Vector\\n  (lambda ts\\n    [\\n      (String->Integer (slice 0 4 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 5 7 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 8 10 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 11 13 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 14 16 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 17 19 ts))\\n ]))\\n(let Date/ymd (lambda dt [(get dt 0) (get dt 1) (get dt 2)]))\\n(let ts (events/timestamp))\\n(map (lambda x (Date/ymd (Date/iso-z->Vector x))) ts)"},{"title":"Count events per hour bucket","description":"Use Date/ymdh as a grouping key and count how many rows land in each hour.","code":"(let Date/iso-z->Vector\\n  (lambda ts\\n    [\\n      (String->Integer (slice 0 4 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 5 7 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 8 10 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 11 13 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 14 16 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 17 19 ts))\\n ]))\\n(let Date/ymdh (lambda dt [(get dt 0) (get dt 1) (get dt 2) (get dt 3)]))\\n(let ts (events/timestamp))\\n(Table/entries\\n  (reduce\\n    (lambda (a stamp)\\n      (do\\n        (let bucket (Date/ymdh (Date/iso-z->Vector stamp)))\\n        (if (Table/has? bucket a)\\n            (Table/set! a bucket (+ 1 (Table/get-unsafe bucket a)))\\n            (Table/set! a bucket 1))\\n        a))\\n    (Table/new)\\n    ts))"}]},{"id":"common-recipes","title":"Common Recipes","subtitle":"Copy-paste patterns for filtering, grouping, sorting, joining, and exporting sheet data.","summary":"These recipes are meant to be copied, adapted, and reused when working with column-based sheet data in the app.","tags":["recipes","patterns","columns","tables","csv"],"content":["These examples assume the sheet columns are already exposed as generated functions like people/name or events/timestamp.","Hoist generated columns once with let before looping, reducing, or repeatedly reading sibling values.","The point of these recipes is reuse: copy one, swap the column names, and adapt the predicate or grouping key."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Filter rows by a sibling column","description":"Keep names only from rows where the country column matches the target value.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let countries (people/country))\\n(filter/i (lambda name i (match? (get countries i) \\"US\\")) names)"},{"title":"Count rows matching a condition","description":"Count how many rows belong to the Blue team.","code":"(let teams (people/team))\\n(count (lambda team (match? team \\"Blue\\")) teams)"},{"title":"Group names by team","description":"Reduce one column while pulling the matching value from another column by index.","code":"(let teams (people/team))\\n(let names (people/name))\\n(Table/entries\\n  (reduce/i (lambda (a team i)\\n              (let name (get names i))\\n                (if (Table/has? team a)\\n                    (push! (Table/get-unsafe team a) name)\\n                    (Table/set! a team [name]))\\n                a)\\n            (Table/new)\\n            teams))"},{"title":"Build a lookup table by id-like key","description":"Create a Table where one column becomes the key and another becomes the value.","code":"(let teams (people/team))\\n(let names (people/name))\\n(Table/entries\\n  (reduce/i (lambda (a name i)\\n              (Table/set! a name (get teams i))\\n              a)\\n            (Table/new)\\n            names))"},{"title":"Sort rows by one column but keep the row data together","description":"Zip sibling columns, sort by age, and keep the paired values aligned.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let ages (people/age))\\n(sort (lambda ({_ a} {_ b}) (> a b)) (zip { names ages }))"},{"title":"Keep original row indices while sorting","description":"Enumerate a column first so sorted results still know their original position.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(sort (lambda ({_ a} {_ b}) (> a b)) (enumerate ages))"},{"title":"Export selected columns as CSV text","description":"Transpose selected columns into rows, then hand them to the simple CSV writer.","code":"(let headers [\\"name\\" \\"team\\"])\\n(let names (people/name))\\n(let teams (people/team))\\n(csv/write/simple headers (transpose [names teams]) \\",\\")"},{"title":"Collect distinct values with a Set","description":"Use a Set when you want unique values from a column without repeated matches.","code":"(let teams (people/team))\\n(let seen\\n  (reduce (lambda a team\\n            (do\\n              (Set/add! a team)\\n              a))\\n          (Set/new)\\n          teams))\\n(Set/values seen)"},{"title":"Check whether any row matches","description":"Use some? for existence checks before doing more expensive work.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(some? (lambda age (> age 30)) ages)"},{"title":"Find the first matching row index","description":"Use find when you need the position of the first matching value.","code":"(let countries (people/country))\\n(find (lambda country (match? country \\"DE\\")) countries)"}]},{"id":"advanced-recipes","title":"Advanced Recipes","subtitle":"Copy-paste patterns for date bucketing, duplicate detection, and cycle checks.","summary":"These recipes cover the next layer of common analysis work: time buckets, repeated values, and graph-like relationships between rows.","tags":["recipes","date","duplicates","cycles","analysis"],"tables":[{"name":"events","csv":"timestamp,amount,from_user,to_user\\n2024-03-01T09:12:00Z,50,U1,U2\\n2024-03-01T09:45:00Z,50,U2,U3\\n2024-03-01T10:05:00Z,50,U3,U1\\n2024-03-02T09:00:00Z,25,U4,U5","schema":[{"name":"timestamp","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"amount","type":"Int"},{"name":"from_user","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"to_user","type":"[Char]"}]},{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE\\nJill,21,Blue,US","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"content":["These recipes are still meant to be copied and adapted. Replace the sheet and column names, keep the pattern.","For timestamp work, parse to integer vectors first and then group on smaller projected buckets like [year month day] or [year month day hour].","For duplicate and graph problems, prefer Tables for grouping and row indices or edges for relationships."],"examples":[{"title":"Count events per day bucket","description":"Parse each ISO timestamp, keep [year month day], and count how many rows land in each day.","code":"(let Date/iso-z->Vector\\n  (lambda ts\\n    [\\n      (String->Integer (slice 0 4 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 5 7 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 8 10 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 11 13 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 14 16 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 17 19 ts))\\n ]))\\n(let Date/ymd (lambda dt [(get dt 0) (get dt 1) (get dt 2)]))\\n(let ts (events/timestamp))\\n(Table/entries\\n  (reduce (lambda (a stamp)\\n            (do\\n              (let bucket (Date/ymd (Date/iso-z->Vector stamp)))\\n              (if (Table/has? bucket a)\\n                  (Table/set! a bucket (+ 1 (Table/get-unsafe bucket a)))\\n                  (Table/set! a bucket 1))\\n              a))\\n          (Table/new)\\n          ts))"},{"title":"Find duplicate rows by a composite key","description":"Group by a tuple key and keep only the keys that appear more than once.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let ages (people/age))\\n(Table/entries\\n  (reduce/i (lambda (a name i)\\n              (do\\n                (let key { name (get ages i) })\\n                (if (Table/has? key a)\\n                    (Table/set! a key (+ 1 (Table/get-unsafe key a)))\\n                    (Table/set! a key 1))\\n                a))\\n            (Table/new)\\n            names))"},{"title":"Keep only duplicated values","description":"Build counts first, then filter a column down to only the values that appear more than once.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let counts\\n  (reduce (lambda a name\\n            (do\\n              (if (Table/has? name a)\\n                  (Table/set! a name (+ 1 (Table/get-unsafe name a)))\\n                  (Table/set! a name 1))\\n              a))\\n          (Table/new)\\n          names))\\n(filter (lambda name (> (Table/get-unsafe name counts) 1)) names)"},{"title":"Check whether a graph has any cycle","description":"Treat two columns as directed edges and ask whether the resulting graph contains a cycle.","code":"(let from (events/from_user))\\n(let to (events/to_user))\\n(let rows (range 0 (- (length from) 1)))\\n(graph/has-cycle? rows from to)"},{"title":"Find increasing-time cycles","description":"Use the graph helper when rows are directed edges and timestamps must increase along the cycle.","code":"(let Date/iso-z->Vector\\n  (lambda ts\\n    [\\n      (String->Integer (slice 0 4 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 5 7 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 8 10 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 11 13 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 14 16 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 17 19 ts))\\n ]))\\n(let Timestamp/seconds\\n  (lambda ts\\n    (+ (* (- (String->Integer (slice 8 10 ts)) 1) 86400)\\n       (* (String->Integer (slice 11 13 ts)) 3600)\\n       (* (String->Integer (slice 14 16 ts)) 60)\\n       (String->Integer (slice 17 19 ts)))))\\n(let rows (range 0 (- (length (events/from_user)) 1)))\\n(graph/find-cycles/increasing-time\\n  rows\\n  (events/from_user)\\n  (events/to_user)\\n  (map Timestamp/seconds (events/timestamp))\\n  3\\n  (* 48 3600))"}]}]'),t=JSON.parse(`[{"id":"core-expressions","title":"Core Expressions","subtitle":"Calls, application order, bindings, sequencing, and unit.","summary":"The language is expression-oriented, function application is left-associated, and local bindings are immutable.","tags":["core","expressions","application"],"content":["Function call: (f a b)","Nested application works: ((f a) b)","Function application is left-associated: (f a b c) means (((f a) b) c), so calling with fewer arguments returns a partially applied function.","(apply f a b) is an alias for nested application, so (apply (f a) b) matches ((f a) b).","Everything is an expression; the last expression is the return value.","(let name value) creates immutable bindings.","(do e1 e2 ... en) evaluates in order, returns en, and does not create a new scope.","Unit is 0 (nil)."],"examples":[{"title":"Sequence and return the last expression","description":"Use do to bind intermediate values and return the last one.","code":"(do\\n  (let x 10)\\n  (let y 20)\\n  (+ x y))"},{"title":"Nested application","description":"Apply a returned function to another argument.","code":"((lambda x (lambda y (+ x y))) 10 5)"}]},{"id":"core-control","title":"Control","subtitle":"Conditionals and looping.","summary":"Use if, cond, and while for branching and iteration, with branch types staying aligned.","tags":["core","control","branching"],"content":["(if cond then else)","(cond c1 e1 c2 e2 ... default)","Branches must return the same type.","Loop with (while cond body).","Loop/for is a convenient counted loop macro: (loop/for i start cond step body ...)."],"examples":[{"title":"Basic if","description":"Choose between two values based on a condition.","code":"(if (> 10 5) 1 0)"},{"title":"cond chain","description":"Evaluate multiple conditions in order and return the matching branch.","code":"(cond false 1 false 2 true 3 4)"},{"title":"While loop with state","description":"Use while to update local state until the condition becomes false.","code":"(mut i 0)\\n(let out [])\\n(while (< i 5)\\n  (push! out i)\\n  (++ i))\\nout"},{"title":"Counted loop with loop/for","description":"Use loop/for when you want a simple counted loop with an index variable.","code":"(let out [])\\n(loop/for i 0 (< i 5) (++ i)\\n  (push! out (* i i)))\\nout"},{"title":"Classify a score with cond","description":"Use cond for a realistic multi-branch decision where conditions are checked in order.","code":"(let score 78)\\n(cond (>= score 90) \\"A\\"\\n      (>= score 80) \\"B\\"\\n      (>= score 70) \\"C\\"\\n      (>= score 60) \\"D\\"\\n      \\"F\\")"}]},{"id":"core-functions","title":"Functions","subtitle":"Lambdas, recursion, destructuring, and collection helpers.","summary":"Functions are built with lambda, recursion goes through letrec, parameters can destructure tuples and vectors, and Table/Set helpers are useful for data-heavy code.","tags":["core","functions","lambda","table","set"],"content":["(lambda a b body)","Recursive functions must use letrec: (letrec f (lambda ... (f ...)))","Destructuring works in params.","Tuples: {a b}","Vectors: [a b c]","'_' skips or ignores a binding slot.","Vectors use explicit rest: [a b c . rest].","Table helpers are good for building lookups and grouped accumulators: Table/new, Table/has?, Table/get-unsafe, Table/set!, Table/entries.","Set helpers are good for deduping and membership checks: Set/new, Set/add!, Set/has?, Set/values."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,country,team\\nJill,US,Blue\\nTom,GB,Blue\\nAnna,US,Red\\nMina,DE,Red","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Tuple destructuring in params","description":"Take apart a tuple directly in the lambda parameter list.","code":"((lambda {a b} (+ a b)) {10 20})"},{"title":"Simple letrec","description":"Define a recursive function with letrec.","code":"(letrec countdown (lambda n (if (= n 0) 0 (countdown (- n 1))))) (countdown 3)"},{"title":"Recursive Fibonacci","description":"Use letrec when a function needs to call itself more than once.","code":"(letrec fibonacci (lambda n (if (< n 2) n (+ (fibonacci (- n 1)) (fibonacci (- n 2))))))\\n(fibonacci 10)"},{"title":"Memoized Fibonacci with a Table","description":"Store previously computed results in a Table so later recursive calls can reuse them.","code":"(letrec fibonacci! (lambda memo n\\n    (do \\n    (let key (Integer->String n))\\n    (if (< n 2) n (if (Table/has? key memo) (snd (first (Table/get key memo))) (do \\n      (let res (+ (fibonacci! memo (- n 1)) (fibonacci! memo (- n 2))))\\n      (Table/set! memo key res)\\n      res))))))\\n\\n(fibonacci! (Table/new) 10)"},{"title":"Build a lookup table from sheet columns","description":"Hoist the generated columns once, then reduce them into a Table keyed by team.","code":"(let teams (people/team))\\n(let names (people/name))\\n(Table/entries\\n  (reduce/i (lambda (a team i)\\n              (let name (get names i))\\n                (if (Table/has? team a)\\n                    (push! (Table/get-unsafe team a) name)\\n                    (Table/set! a team [name]))\\n                a)\\n            (Table/new)\\n            teams))"},{"title":"Collect distinct countries with a Set","description":"Hoist the country column once and fold it into a Set to remove duplicates.","code":"(let countries (people/country))\\n(let seen\\n  (reduce (lambda a country\\n            (do\\n              (Set/add! a country)\\n              a))\\n          (Set/new)\\n          countries))\\n(Set/values seen)"}]},{"id":"core-destructuring","title":"Destructuring","subtitle":"Bind tuple and vector shapes directly in lambda parameters and let bindings.","summary":"Destructuring lets you pull apart tuples and vectors where you bind them, including nested shapes and skipped positions.","tags":["core","destructuring","lambda","let","tuple","vector"],"content":["Tuple destructuring works in lambda parameters and let bindings: {a b}.","Vector destructuring works in lambda parameters and let bindings: [a b c].","'_' skips a slot you do not want to bind.","Vector patterns support explicit rest bindings: [a b . rest].","Patterns can be nested, so you can unpack a tuple or vector inside another shape."],"examples":[{"title":"Tuple destructuring in lambda","description":"Bind both tuple fields directly in the parameter list.","code":"((lambda {a b} (+ a b)) {10 20})"},{"title":"Tuple destructuring in let","description":"Pull tuple fields into local names with one binding.","code":"(let {name country} {\\"Jill\\" \\"US\\"})\\n{ name country }"},{"title":"Vector destructuring in lambda","description":"Bind vector positions directly in the parameter list.","code":"((lambda [a b c] (+ a b c)) [1 2 3])"},{"title":"Vector destructuring in let","description":"Bind vector positions once and reuse the local names below.","code":"(let [first second third] [10 20 30])\\n{ first second third }"},{"title":"Nested destructuring","description":"Unpack nested tuple and vector structure in one pattern.","code":"(let {person [city country]} {\\"Jill\\" [\\"Sofia\\" \\"BG\\"]})\\n{ person city country }"}]},{"id":"core-macros","title":"Macros","subtitle":"Compile-time code generation and inspection.","summary":"Macros are top-level, run before type inference, and work by building syntax through quote, qq, uq, and related helpers.","tags":["core","macros","compile-time"],"content":["Top-level only: (letmacro name ...)","Single-clause: (letmacro inc1 (lambda x (qq (+ (uq x) 1))))","Multi-clause by arity: (letmacro unless ((cond) ...) ((cond body) ...) ((cond then else) ...))","Variadic params use '.' before the rest name: (lambda cond . body ...)","quote returns syntax as data; qq builds syntax conveniently.","qq builds syntax, uq inserts one syntax value, uqs splices a rest syntax list into qq.","gensym returns a fresh syntax name for generated bindings.","Macro bodies can use compile-time do and let.","(macroexpand-1 expr) expands one macro layer and returns the expanded source as a string.","(macroexpand expr) fully expands recursively and returns the expanded source as a string.","Macros run at compile time before type inference; infer only sees the expanded result."],"examples":[{"title":"Single-clause macro","description":"Define a small macro and use it immediately.","code":"(do\\n  (letmacro inc1 (lambda x (qq (+ (uq x) 1))))\\n  (inc1 5))"},{"title":"Inspect an expansion","description":"See one step of macro expansion as source text.","code":"(do\\n  (letmacro inc1 (lambda x (qq (+ (uq x) 1))))\\n  (macroexpand-1 (inc1 5)))"}]},{"id":"core-types","title":"Types","subtitle":"Primitive values, vectors, tuples, and suffix conventions.","summary":"The language has primitive numeric, boolean, and character types, homogeneous vectors, tuples, and [Char] strings.","tags":["core","types","literals"],"content":["Int, Dec, Bool, Char","Vector [T] (homogeneous)","Tuple {A B}","String is [Char]","Equality example: = (Int), =. (Dec), =# (Char), =? (Bool)","Operator suffixes: '.' for Dec, '#' for Char, '?' for Bool.","String literal uses double quotes, e.g. \\"Hello World\\".","Char literal uses single quotes, e.g. 'a'."],"examples":[{"title":"Literal values","description":"Build a tuple that mixes multiple core literal types.","code":"{1 2.5 true 'a' \\"Hello\\"}"},{"title":"Typed equality","description":"Use the suffix-aware equality operators.","code":"{(= 2 2) (=. 2.5 2.5) (=# 'a' 'a') (=? true true)}"}]},{"id":"core-pipes","title":"Pipe Operators","subtitle":"Left-to-right data flow and function composition.","summary":"Use |> for value-first flow and comp to build composed functions.","tags":["core","pipes","composition"],"content":["(|> x f g h) means (h (g (f x))) (left-to-right flow with data last).","(comp f g h) builds a function equivalent to (lambda x (h (g (f x))))"],"examples":[{"title":"Pipe a value through steps","description":"Transform a value left to right with |>.","code":"(let add1 (lambda x (+ x 1)))\\n(let mul2 (lambda x (* x 2)))\\n(|> 5 add1 mul2)"},{"title":"Build a composed function","description":"Compose functions first, then apply the result.","code":"(let add1 (lambda x (+ x 1)))\\n(let mul2 (lambda x (* x 2)))\\n((comp add1 mul2) 5) ((comp add1 mul2) 5)"}]},{"id":"core-mutation","title":"Mutation and Effects","subtitle":"Local mutation, boxed mutation, vector updates, and naming rules.","summary":"Mutation is explicit, effects are marked with !, and argument ordering matters for mutating functions.","tags":["core","mutation","effects"],"content":["mut/alter! are for local primitive scalar mutation only (Int/Dec/Bool/Char), same lambda scope.","&mut/&alter! are for shared mutation across lambda scopes via boxed references.","Vector/state mutation uses set!, push!, pop!.","Functions with side effects (mutation or I/O) must end with !.","If a function mutates args, the mutated arg must be the first arg.","If mutating multiple values, pass them inside the first arg (typically a tuple)."],"examples":[{"title":"Push into a vector","description":"Mutate a vector state and inspect the result.","code":"(let xs [1 2 3])\\n(push! xs 4)\\nxs"},{"title":"Set an element","description":"Update a vector position with set! and return the new vector.","code":"(let xs [10 20 30])\\n(set! xs 1 99)\\nxs"}]},{"id":"core-builtins","title":"Built-ins","subtitle":"Core data access, arithmetic, bitwise operations, conversions, and booleans.","summary":"The language ships with a broad set of built-ins for vectors, tuples, numeric operations, bitwise ops, and basic constants.","tags":["core","builtins","operators"],"content":["set! pop! length get car cdr cons fst snd while","cons prepends a value to the front of a vector or string-like [Char] sequence.","+ - * / mod = < > <= >= +. -. *. /. mod. =. <. >. <=. >=. +# -# *# /# =# =?","and or not & | ^ >> << ~ Int->Dec Dec->Int true false nil"],"examples":[{"title":"Use a few structural built-ins","description":"Read length, the first element, and the tail of a vector.","code":"{(length [1 2 3]) (car [1 2 3]) (cdr [1 2 3])}"},{"title":"Numeric and conversion built-ins","description":"Mix integer arithmetic, decimal conversion, and booleans.","code":"{(+ 2 3) (Int->Dec 7) (and true false) (~ 1)}"},{"title":"Prepend with cons","description":"Use cons to add one value at the front of an existing vector.","code":"(cons [1 2 3] [4 5 6])"}]}]`),a=JSON.parse(`[{"id":"range-reference","title":"range","subtitle":"Create a numeric sequence directly in the editor.","summary":"Use range when you need a simple generated sequence without depending on a sheet.","tags":["reference","sequence","int"],"content":["Range is useful for quick experimentation and generated examples when you want a predictable sequence of integers.","Because this reference is editor-only, it does not rely on imported sheet data."],"examples":[{"title":"Create a basic range","description":"Generate a sequence directly from the editor.","code":"(range 0 10)"}]},{"id":"map-reference","title":"map","subtitle":"Transform each value in a sheet-backed column.","summary":"Map applies a function to every element of a vector and returns a new vector.","tags":["reference","transform","vector"],"content":["Map is the standard way to transform an entire column without mutating the source data.","A common use is deriving a new set of values from a sheet column before binding the result locally."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Increment every age","description":"Map over a generated column from the people sheet.","code":"(map (lambda age (+ age 1)) (people/age))"}]},{"id":"filter-reference","title":"filter","subtitle":"Keep only the values that match a condition.","summary":"Filter removes elements that do not satisfy the predicate.","tags":["reference","predicate","vector"],"content":["Filter is useful when you want to narrow a sheet column down to only the rows that matter for the current idea.","It preserves the original order while excluding values that fail the predicate."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Keep adult ages","description":"Filter a generated age column from the people sheet.","code":"(filter (lambda age (> age 25)) (people/age))"}]},{"id":"reduce-reference","title":"reduce","subtitle":"Collapse a whole column into one value.","summary":"Reduce walks a vector and combines its elements into a single result.","tags":["reference","aggregate","vector"],"content":["Reduce is the standard pattern for totals, counts, and any other aggregation over a sheet column.","It takes an accumulator, a current value, and produces a new accumulator at each step."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Sum ages","description":"Reduce a generated age column from the people sheet into one total.","code":"(reduce (lambda total age (+ total age)) 0 (people/age))"}]},{"id":"map-filter-composition","title":"map + filter","subtitle":"Compose transformations and predicates over sheet data.","summary":"Once data lives in a sheet column, map and filter can be chained to build more focused derived views.","tags":["reference","composition","sheets"],"content":["The generated sheet column functions work well as the source for multiple higher-order operations in a row.","This kind of composition is a good way to explore data quickly before committing to a larger expression."],"tables":[{"name":"scores","csv":"player,score\\nAda,14\\nBen,9\\nCleo,17","schema":[{"name":"player","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"score","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Boost only higher scores","description":"Filter first, then map over the remaining sheet values.","code":"(map (lambda score (+ score 1)) (filter (lambda score (> score 10)) (scores/score)))"}]},{"id":"zip-reference","title":"zip","subtitle":"Combine multiple columns position by position into tuples.","summary":"Zip is useful when related values live in separate columns and you want to process them row by row together.","tags":["reference","zip","columns","tuples"],"content":["Zip turns parallel vectors into one vector of tuples.","This is especially useful with sheet columns because generated columns are already separate vectors."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Pair names and ages","description":"Read both generated columns once and zip them into row tuples.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let ages (people/age))\\n(zip { names ages })"}]},{"id":"unzip-reference","title":"unzip","subtitle":"Split a vector of tuples back into parallel vectors.","summary":"Unzip is the inverse of zip and is useful when you want to recover separate columns after tuple-based processing.","tags":["reference","unzip","columns","tuples"],"content":["Unzip takes a vector of pairs and returns a tuple of vectors.","This is useful after sorting, mapping, or filtering zipped row data when you want the columns back separately."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Recover separate columns after zipping","description":"Zip two columns, then unzip them back into parallel vectors.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let ages (people/age))\\n(unzip (zip { names ages }))"}]},{"id":"enumerate-reference","title":"enumerate","subtitle":"Attach row indices to a column.","summary":"Enumerate is useful when row position matters and you want each value paired with its index.","tags":["reference","enumerate","rows","indices"],"content":["Enumerate returns tuples of index and value.","This is useful for sorting while keeping row positions, building lookup tables, or filtering based on both the value and the row."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Keep each age with its row index","description":"Enumerate the generated age column to see index-value pairs.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(enumerate ages)"}]},{"id":"sort-reference","title":"sort","subtitle":"Reorder values with a custom comparison function.","summary":"Sort is useful when you want a derived order in code, not just in the sheet UI.","tags":["reference","sort","order","vector"],"content":["Sort takes a comparator lambda and returns a reordered vector.","A common pattern is to sort enumerated or zipped data, then project the fields you want afterward."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Sort ages descending while keeping indices","description":"Enumerate first so the original row positions stay attached to the values.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(sort (lambda ({_ a} {_ b}) (> a b)) (enumerate ages))"}]},{"id":"join-reference","title":"join","subtitle":"Combine many text values with a separator.","summary":"Join is useful when you want to turn a vector of strings into one formatted text value.","tags":["reference","join","text","vector"],"content":["Join takes a separator string and a vector of strings.","This is useful for CSV-like formatting, labels, debug output, and condensed summaries."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Join names with commas","description":"Read the generated name column once and combine it into one string.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(join \\",\\" names)"}]},{"id":"split-reference","title":"split","subtitle":"Break text apart by a separator string.","summary":"Split is useful when one string contains multiple logical values and you want them back as a vector.","tags":["reference","split","text","vector"],"content":["Split takes a separator string and an input string.","It is useful for parsing lightweight delimited data or breaking a label into parts before further processing."],"examples":[{"title":"Split a comma-separated string","description":"Break one text value into multiple parts.","code":"(split \\",\\" \\"Jill,Tom,Anna\\")"}]},{"id":"reverse-reference","title":"reverse","subtitle":"Flip a vector so the last value becomes the first.","summary":"Reverse is useful when you want to inspect column values from the opposite end without mutating the source.","tags":["reference","reverse","vector"],"content":["Reverse returns a new vector in the opposite order.","This is helpful for quickly inspecting the tail of a column first or for pairing reversed values with other derived logic."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Reverse a numeric column","description":"Read the generated age column once and return it in reverse order.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(reverse ages)"}]},{"id":"select-reference","title":"select","subtitle":"Keep only the values that match a predicate.","summary":"Select is an alias for filtering in the positive sense: keep what matches and drop the rest.","tags":["reference","select","predicate","vector"],"content":["Select is useful when the positive wording reads more naturally than filter.","It returns only the values for which the predicate returns true, preserving the original order."],"tables":[{"name":"scores","csv":"player,score\\nAda,14\\nBen,9\\nCleo,17","schema":[{"name":"player","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"score","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Select only higher scores","description":"Keep the score values that pass the predicate.","code":"(let scores (scores/score))\\n(select (lambda score (> score 10)) scores)"}]},{"id":"exclude-reference","title":"exclude","subtitle":"Drop the values that match a predicate.","summary":"Exclude is the inverse of select: it keeps values that do not satisfy the predicate.","tags":["reference","exclude","predicate","vector"],"content":["Exclude is useful when you want to remove unwanted values without writing an explicit not around the predicate.","It preserves the order of the remaining values while discarding the ones that match."],"tables":[{"name":"scores","csv":"player,score\\nAda,14\\nBen,9\\nCleo,17","schema":[{"name":"player","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"score","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Exclude lower scores","description":"Drop the score values that match the low-score predicate.","code":"(let scores (scores/score))\\n(exclude (lambda score (<= score 10)) scores)"}]},{"id":"slice-reference","title":"slice","subtitle":"Take a bounded section of a vector by start and end index.","summary":"Slice is useful when you want a middle segment of a column rather than only the front or back.","tags":["reference","slice","vector"],"content":["Slice returns the values from start up to but not including end.","It is useful for sampling a section of a column, trimming headers or trailers, or building windowed logic."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Slice the middle of a column","description":"Read the generated age column once and take only the selected range.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(slice 1 3 ages)"}]},{"id":"take-first-reference","title":"take/first","subtitle":"Keep the first n values from a vector.","summary":"Take/first is a quick way to grab the front of a generated column without writing an explicit slice.","tags":["reference","take","vector"],"content":["Take/first returns the first n values from a vector in the same order.","This is useful when you only want a preview of the column or when you want a small leading subset for experimentation."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Take the first two ages","description":"Read the generated age column once and keep only the first two values.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(take/first 2 ages)"}]},{"id":"take-last-reference","title":"take/last","subtitle":"Keep the last n values from a vector.","summary":"Take/last is useful when the most recent or trailing values are the ones you care about.","tags":["reference","take","vector"],"content":["Take/last returns the trailing n values from a vector.","It is useful for recent rows, trailing samples, or inspecting the end of a generated column."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Take the last two ages","description":"Read the generated age column once and keep the trailing values.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(take/last 2 ages)"}]},{"id":"drop-first-reference","title":"drop/first","subtitle":"Skip the first n values and keep the rest.","summary":"Drop/first is useful when you want to ignore leading values without rewriting the whole vector pipeline.","tags":["reference","drop","vector"],"content":["Drop/first removes the first n values and returns the remaining tail.","This is useful for skipping warm-up rows, headers that were already handled elsewhere, or the front of a generated column."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Drop the first age","description":"Read the generated age column once and skip the first value.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(drop/first 1 ages)"}]},{"id":"drop-last-reference","title":"drop/last","subtitle":"Drop the last n values and keep the front.","summary":"Drop/last is useful when the tail contains values you want to ignore while keeping the leading rows intact.","tags":["reference","drop","vector"],"content":["Drop/last removes the trailing n values from a vector.","It is useful when the end of a column contains incomplete rows, temporary values, or any tail segment you want to ignore."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Drop the last age","description":"Read the generated age column once and remove the trailing value.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(drop/last 1 ages)"}]},{"id":"reduce-i-reference","title":"reduce/i","subtitle":"Reduce one column while reading matching values from another by row index.","summary":"Use reduce/i when one column drives the loop but the result depends on sibling columns too.","tags":["reference","reduce/i","rows","table"],"content":["Reduce/i passes both the current value and its row index.","This is useful with sheet columns because you can read matching values from another column without rebuilding rows first."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Build a name lookup by team","description":"Reduce the team column while reading the matching name from the same row.","code":"(let teams (people/team))\\n(let names (people/name))\\n(Table/entries\\n  (reduce/i (lambda (a team i)\\n              (let name (get names i))\\n                (if (Table/has? team a)\\n                    (push! (Table/get-unsafe team a) name)\\n                    (Table/set! a team [name]))\\n                a)\\n            (Table/new)\\n            teams))"}]},{"id":"filter-i-reference","title":"filter/i","subtitle":"Filter one column using both the value and its row index.","summary":"Use filter/i when the decision depends on another column at the same row.","tags":["reference","filter/i","rows","predicate"],"content":["Filter/i gives the predicate both the current value and its row index.","This makes multi-column filtering straightforward when your data is stored as parallel sheet columns."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Keep names only from the Blue team","description":"Filter the name column by looking at the team value from the same row.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let teams (people/team))\\n(filter/i (lambda name i (match? (get teams i) \\"Blue\\")) names)"}]},{"id":"zip-unzip-reference","title":"zip + unzip","subtitle":"Work on multiple columns together, then split them back out.","summary":"Zip related columns into tuples, transform or reorder them together, then unzip when you want separate vectors again.","tags":["reference","zip","unzip","columns","rows"],"content":["Zip is a good bridge from columnar data to row-like processing.","Unzip lets you come back to separate columns after sorting, filtering, or mapping the zipped tuples."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Zip, reorder, then unzip names and ages","description":"Keep names and ages together while sorting, then split them back into parallel vectors.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let ages (people/age))\\n(|> (zip { names ages })\\n    (sort (lambda ({_ a} {_ b}) (> a b)))\\n    unzip)"}]},{"id":"sort-enumerate-reference","title":"sort + enumerate","subtitle":"Sort values while keeping their original row positions.","summary":"Enumerate first when you need a sorted view but still care where each value came from.","tags":["reference","sort","enumerate","rows","indices"],"content":["Enumerate attaches row indices before sorting.","That makes it possible to sort derived data and still project back into the original columns later."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Sort ages descending and keep row indices","description":"The result keeps both the original row and the value after sorting.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(sort (lambda ({_ a} {_ b}) (> a b)) (enumerate ages))"}]},{"id":"transpose-reference","title":"transpose","subtitle":"Turn columns into rows or rows into columns.","summary":"Transpose is useful when your app stores data in columns but an operation wants row-oriented vectors.","tags":["reference","transpose","columns","rows"],"content":["Transpose swaps the two axes of a rectangular vector of vectors.","A common use is moving from sheet columns to row vectors before formatting or export."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Turn two columns into rows","description":"Build a row-oriented view from separate generated columns.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let ages (people/age))\\n(transpose [names (map Integer->String ages)])"}]},{"id":"table-get-reference","title":"Table/get and Table/get-unsafe","subtitle":"Read from a Table safely or directly when the key is known to exist.","summary":"Use Table/get when the key may be missing and Table/get-unsafe when a prior check guarantees it exists.","tags":["reference","table","lookup","safe"],"content":["Table/get returns matching entries in a safe lookup shape that can be empty.","Table/get-unsafe is for the cases where you already know the key exists, usually after Table/has?."],"examples":[{"title":"Read a known key after checking it exists","description":"Use Table/has? before Table/get-unsafe when you want direct access to the stored value.","code":"(let counts (Table/new))\\n(Table/set! counts \\"Blue\\" 2)\\n(if (Table/has? \\"Blue\\" counts)\\n    (Table/get-unsafe \\"Blue\\" counts)\\n    0)"},{"title":"Use Table/get when the key may be missing","description":"The safe lookup shape can be checked before pulling out the stored value.","code":"(let counts (Table/new))\\n(Table/set! counts \\"Blue\\" 2)\\n(let found (Table/get \\"Red\\" counts))\\n(if (empty? found) 0 (snd (first found)))"}]},{"id":"set-has-reference","title":"Set/has?","subtitle":"Check membership before including or excluding a value.","summary":"Set/has? is useful when you want a quick membership test without building repeated equality checks by hand.","tags":["reference","set","membership","predicate"],"content":["Set/has? answers whether a value has already been inserted into the Set.","This is useful for filtering, deduping workflows, and whitelist or blacklist style checks."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Keep names only from allowed countries","description":"Build a Set once, then use Set/has? inside a row-aware filter.","code":"(let allowed (Set/new))\\n(Set/add! allowed \\"US\\")\\n(Set/add! allowed \\"DE\\")\\n(let names (people/name))\\n(let countries (people/country))\\n(filter/i (lambda name i (Set/has? (get countries i) allowed)) names)"}]},{"id":"some-reference","title":"some?","subtitle":"Return true when at least one value matches a predicate.","summary":"Some? is the short-circuiting \\"any\\" check for vectors.","tags":["reference","some?","predicate","bool"],"content":["Some? walks the vector until one value satisfies the predicate, then returns true.","It is useful for membership-like checks, anomaly detection, and quick existence tests over a column."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Check if any age is above 30","description":"Return true as soon as one age passes the threshold.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(some? (lambda age (> age 30)) ages)"}]},{"id":"every-reference","title":"every?","subtitle":"Return true only when all values match a predicate.","summary":"Every? is the short-circuiting \\"all\\" check for vectors.","tags":["reference","every?","predicate","bool"],"content":["Every? walks the vector until one value fails the predicate, then returns false.","It is useful for validation checks, schema-like guards, and verifying column-wide assumptions."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Check if every age is above 18","description":"Return false immediately if any value breaks the condition.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(every? (lambda age (> age 18)) ages)"}]},{"id":"some-i-reference","title":"some/i?","subtitle":"Return true when any row satisfies a predicate that uses the row index.","summary":"Some/i? is the indexed short-circuiting \\"any\\" check for vectors.","tags":["reference","some/i?","predicate","rows","bool"],"content":["Some/i? passes both the current value and its row index to the predicate.","This is useful when the condition depends on another column at the same row or on the position itself."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Check if any name belongs to a US row","description":"Use the index to read the matching country from a sibling column.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let countries (people/country))\\n(some/i? (lambda name i (match? (get countries i) \\"US\\")) names)"}]},{"id":"every-i-reference","title":"every/i?","subtitle":"Return true only when every row satisfies a predicate that uses the row index.","summary":"Every/i? is the indexed short-circuiting \\"all\\" check for vectors.","tags":["reference","every/i?","predicate","rows","bool"],"content":["Every/i? passes both the current value and its row index to the predicate.","This is useful when validation depends on sibling columns or on row position, not just on the current value."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Check if every name has a non-empty country","description":"Use the index to validate a related column at each row.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let countries (people/country))\\n(every/i? (lambda name i (not (empty? (get countries i)))) names)"}]},{"id":"upper-reference","title":"upper","subtitle":"Convert characters or text values to uppercase.","summary":"Upper is useful for normalization before grouping, matching, or display.","tags":["reference","upper","text","normalize"],"content":["Upper converts text to uppercase.","This is useful when values should compare case-insensitively or when you want a consistent display form."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Uppercase each name","description":"Normalize a generated text column before further processing.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(map (map upper) names)"}]},{"id":"lower-reference","title":"lower","subtitle":"Convert characters or text values to lowercase.","summary":"Lower is useful for normalization before comparisons or deduping.","tags":["reference","lower","text","normalize"],"content":["Lower converts text to lowercase.","This is useful for case-insensitive matching and for canonicalizing imported text values."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Lowercase each team name","description":"Normalize a generated text column to one case.","code":"(let teams (people/team))\\n(map (map lower) teams)"}]},{"id":"match-reference","title":"match?","subtitle":"Compare two text values for equality.","summary":"Match? is the standard string equality check for [Char] values.","tags":["reference","match?","text","predicate"],"content":["Match? compares two [Char] values.","Use it when filtering, grouping, or branching on string columns."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Keep only US rows by country","description":"Use match? when comparing sheet-backed text values.","code":"(let countries (people/country))\\n(filter (lambda country (match? country \\"US\\")) countries)"}]},{"id":"max-min-reference","title":"max and min","subtitle":"Choose the larger or smaller of two values.","summary":"Max and min are pairwise comparisons, useful inside reducers and small expressions.","tags":["reference","max","min","numeric"],"content":["Max returns the larger of two values and min returns the smaller.","They are useful when updating running bounds one value at a time."],"examples":[{"title":"Compare two ages","description":"Use max and min directly on individual numeric values.","code":"{ (max 21 32) (min 21 32) }"}]},{"id":"maximum-minimum-reference","title":"maximum and minimum","subtitle":"Find the largest or smallest value in a whole vector.","summary":"Maximum and minimum scan an entire numeric vector and return its extreme value.","tags":["reference","maximum","minimum","aggregate"],"content":["Maximum and minimum operate on a full vector rather than on just two values.","These are useful for quick column summaries and bounds checks."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Find the highest and lowest age","description":"Read the age column once and compute both extremes.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n{ (maximum ages) (minimum ages) }"}]},{"id":"zeroes-ones-reference","title":"zeroes and ones","subtitle":"Create vectors filled with a repeated numeric value.","summary":"Zeroes and ones are useful for counters, masks, and quick initialization.","tags":["reference","zeroes","ones","vector"],"content":["Zeroes creates a vector filled with 0 values and ones creates a vector filled with 1 values.","These are useful when you need a starting vector for later updates or comparisons."],"examples":[{"title":"Create two small seed vectors","description":"Build fixed-size vectors of repeated numeric values.","code":"{ (zeroes 5) (ones 5) }"}]},{"id":"empty-reference","title":"empty? and not-empty?","subtitle":"Check whether a vector has any values.","summary":"Empty? and not-empty? are quick guards for branching on whether a collection has content.","tags":["reference","empty?","not-empty?","vector","predicate"],"content":["Empty? returns true when a vector has no elements.","Not-empty? is the inverse and is useful when a non-empty result should trigger more work."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Check filtered results before using them","description":"Branch on whether a filtered vector contains any rows.","code":"(let us (filter (lambda country (match? country \\"US\\")) (people/country)))\\n{ (empty? us) (not-empty? us) }"}]},{"id":"map-until-reference","title":"map/until","subtitle":"Map values until a stop condition becomes true.","summary":"Map/until is useful when you want a transformed prefix of a vector and then want to stop early.","tags":["reference","map/until","short-circuit","vector"],"content":["Map/until transforms values left to right like map, but stops once the stop predicate becomes true.","This is useful for prefix-style processing when the rest of the vector no longer matters."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Increment ages until one reaches 30","description":"Stop transforming as soon as the stop condition is met.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(map/until (lambda age (+ age 1)) (lambda age (>= age 30)) ages)"}]},{"id":"reduce-until-reference","title":"reduce/until","subtitle":"Reduce values until a stop condition becomes true.","summary":"Reduce/until is useful when you want a running result but can stop as soon as a condition is met.","tags":["reference","reduce/until","short-circuit","aggregate"],"content":["Reduce/until updates an accumulator like reduce, but stops once the stop predicate becomes true.","This is useful for partial totals, bounded scans, and early-exit searches that still want an accumulated result."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Sum ages until the total reaches 50","description":"Stop the running reduction once the accumulator is large enough.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(reduce/until (lambda total age (+ total age)) (lambda total _ (>= total 50)) 0 ages)"}]},{"id":"find-reference","title":"find","subtitle":"Return the index of the first value that matches a predicate.","summary":"Find is useful when you need the first matching row position rather than all matching values.","tags":["reference","find","index","predicate"],"content":["Find returns the index of the first value that satisfies the predicate.","This is useful for locating a row and then reading related values from sibling columns using the returned index."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Find the first age above 30","description":"Return the row index of the first matching value.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(find (lambda age (> age 30)) ages)"}]},{"id":"partition-reference","title":"partition","subtitle":"Split a vector into fixed-size chunks.","summary":"Partition is useful when values should be processed in pairs, windows, or small fixed groups.","tags":["reference","partition","chunks","vector"],"content":["Partition groups a vector into consecutive chunks of a fixed size.","This is useful for batching, paired processing, and reconstructing row-like groups from flat vectors."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Partition ages into pairs","description":"Group the age column into fixed-size chunks of two values each.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(partition 2 ages)"}]},{"id":"permutation-reference","title":"permutation","subtitle":"Generate all orderings of the values in a vector.","summary":"Permutation is useful when order matters and you need to explore every possible arrangement.","tags":["reference","permutation","combinatorics","vector"],"content":["Permutation returns every ordering of the input vector.","This is useful for brute-force search, ordering puzzles, and trying all possible arrangements of a small input."],"examples":[{"title":"Permute three values","description":"Generate all possible orderings of a small vector.","code":"(permutation [1 2 3])"}]},{"id":"combination-pairs-reference","title":"combination/pairs","subtitle":"Generate all unique pairs from a vector.","summary":"Combination/pairs is useful when you need every unordered pair without duplicates.","tags":["reference","combination/pairs","pairs","combinatorics"],"content":["Combination/pairs returns all unique 2-element combinations from the input vector.","This is useful for pairwise comparisons, all-vs-all checks, and building pair candidate lists."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Generate all name pairs","description":"Use the generated name column as the source for all unique unordered pairs.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(combination/pairs names)"}]},{"id":"combination-reference","title":"combination","subtitle":"Generate all combinations from a vector.","summary":"Combination is useful when order does not matter and you want subsets grouped by size.","tags":["reference","combination","combinatorics","subset"],"content":["Combination generates combinations from the input vector.","Use it when the problem is about choosing values rather than arranging them."],"examples":[{"title":"Generate combinations of three values","description":"Explore unordered choices rather than ordered arrangements.","code":"(combination [1 2 3])"}]},{"id":"combination-n-reference","title":"combination/n","subtitle":"Generate all combinations of a fixed size.","summary":"Combination/n is useful when you need exactly n chosen values from a larger set.","tags":["reference","combination/n","combinatorics","subset"],"content":["Combination/n returns only combinations of the requested size.","This is useful for fixed-size teams, k-way checks, and bounded candidate generation."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Choose all pairs of names","description":"Pick exactly two values from the generated name column each time.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(combination/n 2 names)"}]},{"id":"subset-reference","title":"subset","subtitle":"Generate subsets of a vector.","summary":"Subset is useful when you want to explore all smaller selections of a set of values.","tags":["reference","subset","combinatorics","vector"],"content":["Subset generates subsets of the input vector.","This is useful for search problems, feature selection, and any logic that needs to consider optional inclusion."],"examples":[{"title":"Generate subsets of a small vector","description":"Explore the possible smaller selections of a set of values.","code":"(subset [1 2 3])"}]},{"id":"count-reference","title":"count","subtitle":"Count how many values satisfy a predicate.","summary":"Count is useful for frequencies, validations, and quick summaries over a column.","tags":["reference","count","predicate","aggregate"],"content":["Count walks a vector and returns how many values satisfy the predicate.","This is useful for totals like how many rows match a condition or how many values fall into a bucket."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Count rows in the US","description":"Use a predicate to count matching text values in a generated column.","code":"(let countries (people/country))\\n(count (lambda country (match? country \\"US\\")) countries)"}]},{"id":"points-reference","title":"points","subtitle":"Collect coordinates that satisfy a predicate in a grid.","summary":"Points is useful when you have a 2D vector and want the coordinates of matching cells.","tags":["reference","points","grid","coordinates"],"content":["Points walks a 2D vector and returns the coordinates of cells that satisfy the predicate.","This is useful for grid problems, board scanning, and extracting interesting positions from matrix-like data."],"examples":[{"title":"Find positive cells in a grid","description":"Return the coordinates of every cell that matches the predicate.","code":"(points (lambda x (> x 0)) [[0 1 0] [2 0 3] [0 0 4]])"}]},{"id":"cartesian-product-reference","title":"cartesian-product","subtitle":"Generate every ordered pair from two vectors.","summary":"Cartesian-product is useful when every value from one vector must be paired with every value from another.","tags":["reference","cartesian-product","pairs","combinatorics"],"content":["Cartesian-product builds all ordered combinations across two input vectors.","This is useful for search, test cases, cross joins, and comparing every candidate from one set against every candidate from another."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Pair every team with every country","description":"Build all ordered pairs across two generated columns.","code":"(let teams (people/team))\\n(let countries (people/country))\\n(cartesian-product teams countries)"}]},{"id":"window-reference","title":"window","subtitle":"Take sliding windows across a vector.","summary":"Window is useful for local comparisons, rolling calculations, and adjacent pattern checks.","tags":["reference","window","sliding","vector"],"content":["Window returns overlapping slices of a fixed size as it moves across the vector.","This is useful for moving averages, adjacent comparisons, and detecting short local patterns."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Create windows of two ages","description":"Build overlapping local views of a numeric column.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(window 2 ages)"}]},{"id":"map-until-i-reference","title":"map/until/i","subtitle":"Map values until a stop condition becomes true, with access to row indices.","summary":"Map/until/i is useful when the transform or stop condition depends on sibling columns or row position.","tags":["reference","map/until/i","short-circuit","rows"],"content":["Map/until/i works like map/until, but both the mapping function and the stop predicate receive the row index.","This is useful when early termination depends on another column at the same row."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Increment ages until a Red row is reached","description":"Use the row index to stop based on the matching team column.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(let teams (people/team))\\n(map/until/i (lambda age i (+ age 1)) (lambda age i (match? (get teams i) \\"Red\\")) ages)"}]},{"id":"reduce-until-i-reference","title":"reduce/until/i","subtitle":"Reduce values until a stop condition becomes true, with access to row indices.","summary":"Reduce/until/i is useful when the accumulator and early-stop condition both depend on sibling columns or row position.","tags":["reference","reduce/until/i","short-circuit","rows","aggregate"],"content":["Reduce/until/i works like reduce/until, but the reducer and stop predicate also receive the row index.","This is useful when the running result depends on several columns but you still want to stop early."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Sum ages until a GB row is reached","description":"Stop the reduction when the related country column hits the chosen boundary.","code":"(let ages (people/age))\\n(let countries (people/country))\\n(reduce/until/i (lambda total age i (+ total age)) (lambda total _ i (match? (get countries i) \\"GB\\")) 0 ages)"}]},{"id":"for-until-i-reference","title":"for/until/i","subtitle":"Run an effectful pass until a stop condition becomes true, with access to row indices.","summary":"For/until/i is useful when you want side effects over an initial prefix determined by sibling columns or row position.","tags":["reference","for/until/i","short-circuit","rows","effects"],"content":["For/until/i works like for/until, but both functions receive the row index.","This is useful for collecting or mutating state while scanning rows until a related condition becomes true."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age,team,country\\nJill,21,Blue,US\\nTom,32,Blue,GB\\nAnna,28,Red,US\\nMina,26,Red,DE","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"},{"name":"team","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"country","type":"[Char]"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Collect names until a GB row is reached","description":"Use the index to stop based on a sibling column while keeping the collected prefix.","code":"(let names (people/name))\\n(let countries (people/country))\\n(let out [])\\n(for/until/i (lambda name i (push! out name)) (lambda name i (match? (get countries i) \\"GB\\")) names)\\nout"}]},{"id":"date-iso-z-vector-reference","title":"Date/iso-z->Vector","subtitle":"Parse an ISO UTC timestamp into integer date parts.","summary":"Date/iso-z->Vector is a practical way to turn timestamp text into a numeric shape you can group, compare, or project from.","tags":["reference","date","timestamp","iso","parse"],"content":["Date/iso-z->Vector parses a timestamp like 2024-03-01T09:12:00Z into [year month day hour minute second].","That numeric form is easier to group and analyze than raw timestamp text when you need date parts explicitly."],"tables":[{"name":"events","csv":"timestamp,amount\\n2024-03-01T09:12:00Z,10\\n2024-03-01T09:45:00Z,15\\n2024-03-01T10:05:00Z,20\\n2024-03-02T09:00:00Z,25","schema":[{"name":"timestamp","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"amount","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Parse one timestamp into integers","description":"Convert a single ISO UTC timestamp into [year month day hour minute second].","code":"(let Date/iso-z->Vector\\n  (lambda ts\\n    [\\n      (String->Integer (slice 0 4 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 5 7 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 8 10 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 11 13 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 14 16 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 17 19 ts))\\n ]))\\n\\n(Date/iso-z->Vector \\"2024-03-01T09:12:00Z\\")"}]},{"id":"date-ymd-reference","title":"Date/ymd","subtitle":"Keep only the year, month, and day from a parsed timestamp.","summary":"Date/ymd is useful for day-level grouping and day buckets.","tags":["reference","date","ymd","bucket","grouping"],"content":["Date/ymd takes a parsed date vector and keeps only [year month day].","Use it when you want daily buckets without caring about hour, minute, or second."],"tables":[{"name":"events","csv":"timestamp,amount\\n2024-03-01T09:12:00Z,10\\n2024-03-01T09:45:00Z,15\\n2024-03-01T10:05:00Z,20\\n2024-03-02T09:00:00Z,25","schema":[{"name":"timestamp","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"amount","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Bucket event timestamps by day","description":"Parse each timestamp and project only the day-level bucket.","code":"(let Date/iso-z->Vector\\n  (lambda ts\\n    [\\n      (String->Integer (slice 0 4 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 5 7 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 8 10 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 11 13 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 14 16 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 17 19 ts))\\n ]))\\n(let Date/ymd (lambda dt [(get dt 0) (get dt 1) (get dt 2)]))\\n(let ts (events/timestamp))\\n(map (lambda x (Date/ymd (Date/iso-z->Vector x))) ts)"}]},{"id":"date-ymdh-reference","title":"Date/ymdh","subtitle":"Keep only the year, month, day, and hour from a parsed timestamp.","summary":"Date/ymdh is useful for hour-level grouping and hourly event counts.","tags":["reference","date","ymdh","bucket","grouping"],"content":["Date/ymdh takes a parsed date vector and keeps only [year month day hour].","Use it when you want hourly buckets while ignoring minute and second noise."],"tables":[{"name":"events","csv":"timestamp,amount\\n2024-03-01T09:12:00Z,10\\n2024-03-01T09:45:00Z,15\\n2024-03-01T10:05:00Z,20\\n2024-03-02T09:00:00Z,25","schema":[{"name":"timestamp","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"amount","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Count events per hour bucket","description":"Group parsed timestamps by hour and count rows in each bucket.","code":"(let Date/iso-z->Vector\\n  (lambda ts\\n    [\\n      (String->Integer (slice 0 4 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 5 7 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 8 10 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 11 13 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 14 16 ts))\\n      (String->Integer (slice 17 19 ts))\\n ]))\\n(let Date/ymdh (lambda dt [(get dt 0) (get dt 1) (get dt 2) (get dt 3)]))\\n(let ts (events/timestamp))\\n(Table/entries\\n  (reduce\\n    (lambda (a stamp)\\n      (do\\n        (let bucket (|> stamp Date/iso-z->Vector Date/ymdh (map Integer->String) (Vector->String '-')))\\n        (if (Table/has? bucket a)\\n            (Table/set! a bucket (+ 1 (Table/get-unsafe bucket a)))\\n            (Table/set! a bucket 1))\\n        a))\\n    (Table/new)\\n    ts))"}]},{"id":"string-column-reference","title":"map over text","subtitle":"Use map with a text column from a sheet.","summary":"Sheet-backed [Char] columns can also be used as the source for higher-order operations.","tags":["reference","text","map"],"content":["Not every reference needs to focus on numbers. A string column can still be a useful source for map when you want to derive or inspect text values.","This example keeps the source in the sheet and works entirely through the generated column function."],"tables":[{"name":"people","csv":"name,age\\nJill,21\\nTom,32\\nAnna,28","schema":[{"name":"name","type":"[Char]"},{"name":"age","type":"Int"}]}],"examples":[{"title":"Inspect names with map","description":"Map over a text column from the people sheet.","code":"(map (lambda name name) (people/name))"}]}]`),n=[{id:"tool-upload",icon:"upload",title:"Import File",subtitle:"Bring CSV data into the workspace.",summary:"Use the upload/import action to load one or more CSV files into the app.",tags:["tool","upload","csv","files"],content:["The import action reads CSV text and creates a sheet in the workspace.","Imported files keep their sheet name, separator, headers, rows, and schema so you can edit them later.","Once imported, sheet columns can be exposed to Que through hidden generated bindings."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-new-sheet",icon:"new",title:"New Sheet",subtitle:"Create a blank sheet without importing a file.",summary:"New Sheet gives you an empty workspace table that you can fill manually.",tags:["tool","sheet","new","blank"],content:["Use New when you want to build a table from scratch instead of importing CSV.","You can add columns, assign types, add rows, edit cells, and rename the sheet later.","Blank sheets work the same as imported ones once they exist in the workspace."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-files",icon:"files",title:"Files",subtitle:"Browse and switch between your sheets.",summary:"The Files tab is the main place for managing imported and blank sheets.",tags:["tool","files","sidebar","sheets"],content:["The Files tab shows every sheet currently in the workspace.","Selecting a file opens its table view so you can edit columns, rows, filters, raw CSV, and output bindings.","This is also where you add more CSV files after the initial workspace setup."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-functions",icon:"functions",title:"Functions",subtitle:"Store reusable Que helpers separately from the main editor.",summary:"Functions give you a small library of reusable code that can be included into hidden context.",tags:["tool","functions","helpers","include"],content:["A saved function has its own code, its own testing area, and can be included or removed from the hidden context.","Included functions are available to the main editor without being visible in the editor buffer.","This makes it easier to keep reusable code separate from the code you are currently writing."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-learn",icon:"learn",title:"Learn",subtitle:"Read concepts, language notes, and function references.",summary:"Learn is the built-in documentation area for the app and the language.",tags:["tool","learn","docs","reference"],content:["The Learn page includes concepts, core language explanations, function reference material, and tool explanations.","Entries can include runnable editor examples and miniature sheets.","The Learn content is lazy-loaded, so it does not affect the app until you open it."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-settings",icon:"settings",title:"Settings",subtitle:"Configure defaults for the workspace.",summary:"Settings control default separator, default types, default values, and theme.",tags:["tool","settings","defaults","theme"],content:["The settings dialog lets you change workspace-level defaults that affect new sheets and imports.","This is where you choose things like default CSV separator, default column type, default values, and theme.","These settings are stored locally so the workspace feels consistent between visits."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-execute",icon:"execute",title:"Execute",subtitle:"Run the current editor code with the hidden prelude.",summary:"Execute compiles the current editor source together with any hidden sheet and included-function bindings.",tags:["tool","execute","run","editor"],content:["When you execute code, the app combines your visible editor source with the hidden prelude and sends that full source to the runtime.","The hidden prelude can include sheet-backed column bindings and any included functions.","Use this when you want to evaluate expressions, inspect results, or test code against your imported data."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-search",icon:"search",title:"Search and Filter",subtitle:"Find matching rows inside a sheet or table result.",summary:"The search tool lets you filter rows by matching values and inspect only the rows you care about.",tags:["tool","search","filter","rows"],content:["Sheet search opens a focused table view where matching rows are shown and searchable values are highlighted.","The same style of search is also used in table-based result views.","This is especially useful for wide or large sheets where manual scanning is too slow."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-raw-csv",icon:"grip",title:"Raw CSV",subtitle:"Switch from table view to raw CSV text editing.",summary:"Raw CSV gives you direct text editing over the current sheet while preserving the same underlying data.",tags:["tool","csv","raw","text"],content:["Raw CSV mode shows the current sheet as plain CSV text with headers first and the current separator preserved.","When you switch back to table view, the text is parsed again and the sheet is rebuilt.","This is useful when bulk editing is easier as text than through cells."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-focus-columns",icon:"eye",title:"Focus Columns",subtitle:"Select the columns you want to work on and fade the rest.",summary:"Column focus helps reduce visual noise and can shrink the generated hidden prelude.",tags:["tool","columns","focus","visibility"],content:["Clicking a column focus control marks that column as selected.","When at least one column is selected, non-selected columns are dimmed so the chosen ones stand out.","Those selected columns are also the ones that are exposed into the hidden prelude for that sheet."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-hide-columns",icon:"eye_off",title:"Hide Other Columns",subtitle:"Temporarily hide non-selected columns after focusing the ones you want.",summary:"Once you have focused some columns, the eye toggle can hide everything else.",tags:["tool","columns","hide","focus"],content:["The hide/show eye toggle only becomes active when at least one column is selected.","Hiding non-selected columns makes the sheet easier to work with when you only care about a subset.","Because hidden columns are also excluded from the prelude copy used for that sheet, this can reduce unnecessary generated bindings."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-bookmark-columns",icon:"bookmark",title:"Bookmark Columns",subtitle:"Mark the columns you want to keep in focus.",summary:"Bookmarking columns is how you tell the app which columns matter right now.",tags:["tool","bookmark","columns","focus"],content:["Each column header has a bookmark-style focus control that toggles selection for that column.","Selected columns stay at full opacity while the rest are dimmed, which gives you a quick visual way to focus on the relevant fields.","Those selected columns are also the ones used when the app creates the reduced hidden prelude for that sheet."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-sort-columns",icon:"sort",title:"Sort",subtitle:"Reorder rows by the values in one column.",summary:"Sorting lets you inspect your sheet or table result in a more meaningful order.",tags:["tool","sort","rows","table"],content:["Sort is available from column headers and also in the reusable table-based modal views.","When you sort, rows are reordered by the values of that column so patterns are easier to inspect.","This is especially useful for output tables, filtered tables, and numeric columns that you want to inspect from low to high."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-drag-columns",icon:"drag",title:"Drag to Reorder Columns",subtitle:"Move columns into the order that makes sense for your task.",summary:"Dragging columns changes the active sheet order and that order is reflected in raw CSV too.",tags:["tool","drag","reorder","columns"],content:["A drag handle appears in the column header on hover, next to the delete control.","Dragging a column updates the actual sheet order, not just the visual layout, so raw CSV and other derived views reflect the new order too.","This is useful when you want the most important columns at the front, but you should expect code that assumes the old order to behave differently afterward."],examples:[]},{id:"tool-type-inference-toggle",icon:"type_inference",title:"Type Inference / LSP Toggle",subtitle:"Turn editor analysis hints on or off.",summary:"The LSP toggle controls hover, diagnostics, completion, and related editor analysis features.",tags:["tool","lsp","diagnostics","hints","editor"],content:["When enabled, the editor runs Que language analysis so you can get hovers, diagnostics, completions, and related help.","When disabled, typing can feel lighter on slower machines or with large hidden sheet data because those checks are skipped.","This toggle is useful when you want to trade editor intelligence for responsiveness."],examples:[]}],s={concepts:e,core:t,references:a,tools:n};export{e as concepts,t as core,s as default,a as references,n as tools};
